SIMPLE: straiten
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Straiten
<hw>Strait"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Straitened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Straitening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make
strait; to make narrow; hence, to contract; to confine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waters, when <qex>straitened</qex>, as at the falls of bridges,
give a roaring noise.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In narrow circuit, <qex>straitened</qex> by a foe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make tense, or tight; to tighten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>straiten</qex> at each end the cord.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To restrict; to distress or embarrass in respect of
means or conditions of life; -- used chiefly in the past participle; --
as, a man <xex>straitened</xex> in his circumstances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strait-handed</ent>⟦br⟧
